metadata.name: Syzers #391
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template. 
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.name: Framed Flowers #36
metadata.description:

metadata.name: Antiflow #292
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." - Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about how opposing forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental law of nature baked into the very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.
tags: chaos opposites retro expressionist antiparticle flow p5js

metadata.name: Anachronous #248
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Mur #325
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #76
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Capture Bigfoot - Wild Paper Series #14
metadata.description:
In the wilderness of the Pacific Northwest, a legendary creature hides.  Some have tried to find proof of its existence, but have failed.  Will you be the one to capture evidence of the elusive Bigfoot?  

This generative work features hand-drawn ink sketches that have been digitally enhanced, and assembled into these beautiful vistas of distant mountains, mid-range foothills, stands on conifers, large boulders, . . . and, of course, the elusive Bigfoot.

Draw the super-rare Squatch Card for an extra bonus!

Functions: 
Press SPACE to download and save image as a png.
Click or tap the canvas to toggle full screen.

Squatch Card Special Function:
Press 'V' to view assets layout card.
Refresh token to toggle back to landscape.

metadata.name: Vulvator #47
metadata.description:
A Collaboration of illustrator and artist Ma-Ka (Martta-Kaisa Virta) and artist Antti Pussinen.
The body-positive artwork explores the diversity and beauty of the vulva.
Instead of anatomic correctness, Ma-Ka tries to capture the the idea and aesthetic philosophy of the Origin of us all. 

There are at least 1632960 different illustration combinations + hash generated colors, backgrounds and textures.

All of them are rare and unique, so no trackable features.

Illustrations and concept by Ma-Ka, Code, colors and textures by Antti Pussinen.
All profits will be split 50/50 by the artists. 

More illustrations from Ma-Ka @
http://makaflux.com/
https://www.instagram.com/makavirta/

metadata.name: Solace #52
metadata.description:
Solace is an algorithm that generates artworks of sand dunes. It draws hundreds of thousands of tiny points according to a probability distribution calculated from the positions of the dunes.

The logic to divide the dunes into light and dark sides is simple, but produces some interesting chaotic behaviour. These are details that weren't hard-coded but emerge organically, such as the patterns on the spines of the dunes or the stripes around their bases.

Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run, especially when the number of dunes is high.

Created by lunarean.
